astern England it often referred to a patch of dry land in a fen. In some cases the surname may be a habitational name from any of several places in England named with this fossilized inflected form, which would originally have been preceded by a preposition, e.g. <i>in the hale</i> or <i>at the hale</i>. This surname is also established in south Wales.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Céile</b> (see   McHale  ).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Halle  ."]},{"name":"Hayles","meanings":["English:","variant of   Hales  .","variant of   Ayles   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Hailes","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Hailes in Colinton (Midlothian), originally in East Lothian, named from the Middle English genitive or plural form of <i>hall</i> ‘hall’.","English: variant of   Hales   (see also   Hayles  )."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Ralph De Hales was born in 1235, in Hales, Norfolk, England, his father, Baron Walter Hale, was 33 and his mother, De Staartson, was 15. He had at least 1 daughter with Denenta Le Clauer. He died in 1252, at the age of 17."},"et":{"1235–1252":"1235–1252","1252–1276":"1252–1276","1202–1253":"1202–1253","1202–1247":"1202–1247","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","1247":"1247","1235":"1235","1202":"1202","1276":"1276","1220":"1220","1253":"1253","1252":"12